  "publishedAt": "2026-06-15T18:38:29.000Z",
  "contentHtml": "<blockquote><p>Champions of a European AI model should ask themselves if a European effort would be more effective than Meta, which this year will spend more on chips (<a href=\"https://investor.atmeta.com/investor-news/press-release-details/2026/Meta-Reports-First-Quarter-2026-Results/default.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">$125 billion</a>) than Germany spends on defense (<a href=\"https://www.sipri.org/media/press-release/2026/global-military-spending-rise-continues-european-and-asian-expenditures-surge\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">$114 billion</a>) and offer salaries of over&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.wired.com/story/mark-zuckerberg-meta-offer-top-ai-talent-300-million/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">$100 million</a>&nbsp;to attract the best researchers, and is still failing to catch up.</p></blockquote>\n<p>Here is <a href=\"https://www.siliconcontinent.com/p/nineteen-thoughts-on-ai-and-europe\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">more from Pieter Garicano and Simon Grimm</a>.&nbsp; Via Jesper.</p>",
